<paragraph blockId="13.[125,895,240,337]" box="[125,238,313,337]" pageId="13" pageNumber="4042">
<emphasis box="[125,238,313,337]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="4042">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[125,1172,362,418]" pageId="13" pageNumber="4042">The name ‘‘gaemluang’’ refers to the yellow spot on the cheeks (in Thai ‘‘gaem’’ means ‘‘cheek’’ and ‘‘luang’’ means ‘‘yellow’’).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[125,230,475,499]" box="[125,230,475,499]" pageId="13" pageNumber="4042">
<emphasis box="[125,230,475,499]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="4042">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[125,1172,524,676]" pageId="13" pageNumber="4042">Mostly yellow (including legs) species; one pair of verticals; occiput narrowly densely greyish pollinose behind eyes and in upper part, otherwise subshining, with yellowish spot near mouth-opening laterally; antenna wholly yellowish brown, postpedicel 4.5 times longer than wide, arista 3.0 times longer than postpedicel; mesonotum and mesopleuron wholly yellow.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[125,332,754,778]" box="[125,332,754,778]" pageId="13" pageNumber="4042">
<emphasis box="[125,332,754,778]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="4042">Material examined</emphasis>
</paragraph>
